column6: Live at the Ironwood - ROOKS - Canadian Rock & Roll
column8:
Been far too long since our Casat Deck Stage rocked the way it's gonna rock this Friday Night. Time to rectify the situation and put our Age of Aquarium sound booth to the max test. The Ironwood is very pleased to announce we have ROOKS playing our first live Friday night in 101 Days!

Seating is limited to be compliant with COVID-19 restrictions so reserve early. Cover $15 403.269.5581 A limited menu of Ironwood favourites will be available for your dining pleasure. 

Now about ROOKS... 

ROOKS is a 3 piece rock band which formed in Calgary, Alberta, Canada in July 2018. The band features Jay Bowcott on guitar and vocals, Darryl Swart on drums and Brent Rossall on bass. Their sound is unapologetic guitar rock, drawing influences from bands like Thin Lizzy, The Rolling Stones and The Black Keys.

Originally called Bowcott and the New World, the band are established members of the Canadian music scene and were introduced by ex-The Daggersguitarist, Chris Walsh, who was working with both Swart and Bowcott on separate projects. “I was looking for a drummer for a new album I was working on and Chris suggested that Darryl would be a perfect fit,” says Jay. 

After their first meeting, things developed quickly and within a few months, they had added Brent on bass and recorded a 4 song EP called Extended Play Number 1. “It started out as a solo project but I realized really quickly that everyone was contributing equally so we decided to make it a band.” 

After a whirlwind year touring western and central Canada, the band headed back into the studio in October 2019 to record their debut full-length album which coincided with their name change. “People struggled to know how to pronounce our name and we even got confused for New Order (the 80S British band) once.” laughs Swart. 

“From day one I was uncomfortable with my name being in the band name, so Brent suggested the name ROOKS and it immediately stuck. It has a personal meaning to us and some great imagery which inspired the sound on the new album,” adds Jay.

TOM PHILLIPS with Kit Johnson & Tim Leacock
column8:
The tradition continues at the Ironwood in the Age of Aquarium. Tom Phillips takes the Casat Deck at the Ironwood for the 13th year in a row on Parade Day, joined this year by Kit Johnson and Tim Leacock. Due to limited seating and social distancing requirements, reservations are required. 20$ cover charge. Call 403-269-5581 for reservations. Shine up your boots and come on down!!!

Now more about Tom...

TOM PHILLIPS Calgary, Alberta Band leader. Honky-tonk hero. Even soundtrack writer for a book (a Canadian first, for a Will Ferguson novel.) Survivor and singer of cautionary tales. You want it, you got it from Tom Phillips, whose career’s turned itself inside out so often that at times he appears to be a shape shifter. During the past few years, Phillips’ transformation was also physical as he swapped alcohol for coffee and his trademark cowboy boots and shirts for polished shoes and tailored suits. But appearances distract, and Phillips is no shape shifter: if you took a musical x-ray during every incarnation, you’d find song writing as the bedrock under the suits, boots, cowboy hats and skin. Which explains why revered blues artist Eric Bibb covered Phillips’ touchstone tune, Ribbons and Bows, on one of his albums. An esteemed statesperson of the Calgary music scene, Phillips earned his laurels over decades. He recorded with Gordon Lightfoot’s band in Toronto before releasing several albums, both live and in studio, with his legendary long time honky-tonk band The Men of Constant Sorrow (MOCS). He also released an acoustic solo album, paid homage to Hank Williams on the Sorrow Bound project, and smashed his comfort zone with a daring, darling album of cover songs from punk and rock territory. He’s often found anchoring musical gatherings that celebrate the songs of Haggard, Dylan, Springsteen and Lightfoot. 

The evolution continues on his most recent work with the D.T.’s (Difficult Transitions). The band formed serendipitously at bars and open stages, learning Phillips’ most recent songs onstage just in time for his last record. With MOCS veteran Tim Leacock (The Co-Dependents), Ian Grant (Art Bergmann, Cat Ranch), Geoff Brock and sisters Shaye and Sydney Zadravec, the D.T.’s translate Phillips’ songs into live performances that deliver musical delights which offer style without flash. So take a musical walk with Phillips and gaze at life through his seasoned eyes. He’s got it covered with a hundred songs that undress truths so simple they’re frightening. 

Ever cheated on a lover, driven home drunk, been bucked off your horse, or been the last person in the bar when the lights came up? If you’ve been stranded on the highway, woken up in the wrong bed, walked home barefoot in a ball gown in the morning rain, or wished you could have a re-do on any of these choices, Phillips has a song for you. -  MLW   https://www.tomphillipsmusic.com/

TAYLR provides sultry folk reflections, paired with floating melodies. She is versatile artist who provides the perfect soundtrack for the end of the night when you need to figure out if your date wants to kiss you or not. With TAYLR playing, your odds improve, just remember you need to ask first!\r\n\r\nMason Jenkins is an advocate and spokesperson for bringing back the "Calgary Wave" and tries embody the attitude of a very good dog. Jenkins is a transgender man, sharing stories of his adventures in gender and navigating the world as a retired lesbian. His songs are velvet paintings, delightfully campy, and welcomed in any grandmother's living room. Velvet paintings are built on darkness, just like Jenkins’ humour and insights. Contrast is what makes the highlights brighter, any dog could tell you that.

We’re coming together to make beautiful music in support of the Charis Project, a nonprofit working to provide support for at risk migrant families in northern Thailand. This organization is unique in its approach to strengthen families and communities to keep children out of orphanages and trafficking and help them grow up in a loving home. They are committed to healing the root of the problem instead of offering bandaid solutions, with the ultimate goal of putting themselves out of business!  Check them out here www.thecharisproject.org 
You can help! Just come down to the Aviary to hear and witness some magical music made by Bill Bourne, Kimberley MacGregor, Future Ghost Towns and Laurelle Kanji. All ages show that’s sure to be a great time that you can feel good about! Hope to see you there!

column8:
ACT 1: HOLIDAY RADIO PLAY: IT’S AN OKAY LIFE, CONSIDERING
Watch someone’s life transformed this holiday season! This unique show takes its cue from the radio plays popularized in the 1930s and 40s, and from the magic of Frank Capra’s classic film It’s a Wonderful Life.

This completely improvised radio play features live actors, made up stories, improvised product sponsor ads, and live music and sound effects!

Featuring live performances from Mandy Morris and her jazz quartet! Produced in partnership with CJSW.

 

ACT 2: GROUP CHAT FEAT. VLAD & VICKY
Are you perpetually glued to your phone?
Do you create insurmountable barriers to your interpersonal communication skills?
Are you unable to form intimate connections the old-fashioned way?
Same! Group Chat is a troupe of tech-savvy artists who perform improv inspired by your favourite social media platforms – from the trending Tweets to Skype calls with your mom!

Watch these Millennials cope with crushing debt and imminent ecological disaster by laughing at the absurdity of our modern existence!

Tickets for this very special show are $15 each. Students 2-for-1 at the door, with student ID.

Online sales end at 6pm day of the show. A limited number of tickets will be available at the door – we open at 7:30pm.

column6: BEAUTY LOVE TRUTH FEAT. EMILY TRIGGS | DREAM TOAST
column8:
ACT 1: BEAUTY LOVE TRUTH FEAT. EMILY TRIGGS
Beauty Love Truth combines live music and heartfelt improv. Performing scenes inspired by original songs, the improvisers bring new meaning to the lyrics through tales of heartbreak, happiness and hope.

FEATURING GUEST MUSICIAN EMILY TRIGGS
Emily Triggs is a prolific songwriter with a passion for storytelling.  Sometimes likened to Patty Griffin and Michelle Shocked, Emily’s unique brand of folk/roots showcases her honest, pure vocals.

Emily’s debut album ‘When Guinevere Went Under’, received radio play across the country and into the United States. Emily has performed at CBC, Vancouver Folk Music Festival, Calgary Folk Music Festival and Wide Cut Weekend. With her soon-to-be-released album, ‘Middletown, ’Triggs is busting down walls that confine an artist to expectations and genres.

ACT 2: DREAM TOAST
A show based entirely on dream logic where dreams inspire dreams inspire dreams. It gets weird, nothing makes sense and your mom is there with a different face, but in the end it all means something. Delve into your subconscious with Dream Toast and discover the zany world of dream “logic.”

THIS TWO-ACT SHOW RUNS FROM 8PM TO 10PM WITH A BRIEF INTERMISSION.
Tickets are $12 online or $15 at the door.

Online sales end at 6pm day of the show. A limited number of tickets will be available at the door – we open at 7:30pm.

column8:
*NOTE**
Thank you for your support for live music in Calgary! The not-for-profit, all volunteer Music Mile Society of Calgary 
All Tips for this performance goes to the Music Mile Revival Fund for the sole purpose of bringing music back to the Mile. In an effort to support both our venues and our musicians, we will pay local artists to play on Music Mile stages, inside and out, on Friday nights during the post-COVID transitional phase. 

Music is returning to Music Mile once again! As venues begin to re-open
their doors to live audiences and welcome artists back to their stages,
Music Mile is thrilled to announce:

Live from Music Mile: It's Friday Night!

The program showcases five venues every Friday in July, with live music
shows played to in-person audiences and streamed live to music lovers
at home.

Wild T & The Spirit
Friday, November 26th 2021
Tickets only $20 advanced.
Get your tickets now by hitting the Find Tickets button or go to our website https://blindbeggar.ca/buy-tickets/

Doors open at 5:30pm.
Show starts 7:30.
Make it dinner and a show: Buy your show tickets and then add on BBQ Pit Platter for your table.
Come for dinner anytime before your show!
Note: when you purchase your table, you own it for the night.
General Admission tickets do not guarantee a seat or table. First come first serve for any unsold tables.
Thanks for supporting us and Live music.
Check out the video below...............
https://youtu.be/JsWb2u2sGGA
BIO:
Guitarist Toney Springer has hung with the best of them, David Bowie, Jeff Healey, Bon Jovi, Jay Leno, David Letterman and Arsenio Hall. These are a few of the personalities that have been blown away by Toney's music.
Toney aka Wild T took his name from his home town of Tunapuna Trinidad, though one may find similarities to Jimi Hendrix, Lenny Kravitz & Eric Gales ironically it was Toney's exposure to Steve Howe (Yes) that inspired him to pick up guitar.
Moving to Toronto in his early teens, Toney quickly gained a reputation in the mid 80's... After being in Toronto for a few years Toney was voted best guitarist at the Canadian Black Music awards and has not looked back since. Jeff Healey saw a man with endless imagination, a man who could combine that imagination with an emotion that you couldn't help but feel. "I followed him around like he was a Messiah, I probably learned more from Toney than anybody else, Toney's been my idol for years" said Jeff Healy.
Jeff Healey wasn't the only one who noticed Toney's rapid ascension through the ranks. David Bowie chose Toney to be his guitarist on his Black Tie White Noise album after seeing Toney's video for 'Midnight Blues' on a tv show while in Montreal with Tin Machine (Bowie's Supergroup), subsequently Toney appeared with Bowie on Jay Leno, David Letterman & Arsenio Hall & on Bowie's making of Black Tie White Noise dvd prominently showcasing Toney.... "an absolute delight to work with" said Bowie.
The spiritual karma exchanged with his audiences has given Toney a tremendous reputation for firey live performances.
www.wildtandthespirit.com

Curtis is a Nashville based folk artist with a unique and intimate sound. column8: Featuring the sultry voice of Robin Huber, ‘Round Midnight has been wowing audiences with their unique approach to jazz, blues and R&B, from the timeless standards of the 1920’s through to jazz interpretations of contemporary hits.  Whether it’s a slow ballad or an up-tempo bounce tune, Robin’s magical voice blends perfectly with the traditional acoustic jazz combo sound of Shawn Ferguson (tenor sax), Jay Harman (guitar) and Bill Durtler (upright bass). This evening is sure to get your toes tapping and your lips smiling.  To kick off the 2017 Poppy season they will be donating all proceeds from tonight’s show to the Calgary Veteran’s Food Drive.

column6: Give a Mile - Cooking up Christmas Flights!
column8:
Join us in bringing people together for the holidays! In this virtual special event hosted by JD Lewis, and brought to you by Give A Mile, Blue Flame Kitchen, Village Brewery, and Cask Global Canning Solutions, you’ll enjoy live music by Pat Moore, delicious food and local beer.

Proceeds from this event will go to Give A Mile, a charity which provides flights for people to visit with a loved one who is critically ill or dealing with palliative illness.  This holiday season we are looking to give 25 flights away.

During this event, you will enjoy a three-course meal provided by Blue Flame Kitchen with Village Brewery beer paired with each course. Don’t eat too quickly, as there will be a chef demonstration that will go along your main course with none other than Blue Flame Kitchen's chef Darcy!

You’ll hear speeches from sponsors, connect with community and ultimately give to a great cause.
The Frontiers are an independent Albertan Folk Rock band. They marry aggressive vocals, powerful tempos, and progressive instrument riffs with roots/folk rhythms and lyrics that tell a story.

Laura Jackson and Brad Taylor bring diverse musical backgrounds to their show. When their sonic worlds smashed together they ended up with cool takes on a bunch of tunes. Travel with them through a selection of pop, indie, roots, jazz, blues & soul music.

Drawing from the American tradition of blues, country and rock, his songs are like going canoeing with John Lennon and Tom Sawyer. He'll be showcasing new songs written during his recent music residency at the Banff Centre for Arts and Creativity.

Mister and Mystic is a duo that offers strong vocals with introspective lyrics submerged in atmospheric guitar and piano. A very intimate and personal outlet that ventures into baroque pop, bedroom pop, trip-hop, and folk.”

Ms. Oai is known for a earthy jazzy soulful tones.  Singing with Greats such as Thomas Alexander and Grammy Award Winner Donald Ray Johnson as a Raylette in the Ray Charles Tribute Orchestra.  Her humble beginnings singing hymns with her family in Setswana an African language brought out a unique musical passion; that propelled her into singing gospel with her church.  Where she performed solos at the Jubillee Auditorium, Jack Singer Concert Hall for Black History Concerts, CTV News, and opening for the late Coretta Scott King.

Born & raised in Calgary Alberta, Phenix's songs tell of the faith, love & loss found between the open prairies & towering Rocky Mountains of Southern Alberta. Phenix’s distinct sound is grounded in lush acoustic guitars, lo-fi basement recordings, nostalgic drum sounds & winding pedal steel. His debut album Nothing But The Blood, intertwines ideas of love, christianity & self acceptance in a unique & mature way for a first release. Phenix also produces records with artists such as Heather May, Luke Nielsen, Wyatt C Louis & others across the Canadian music scene at his studio in Calgary “Alta Sound”.

Aaron Pollock is a country singer/songwriter from Calgary, AB. Bringing together contemporary country songwriting with John Mayer-influenced guitar playing, Aaron is currently working on writing songs for an upcoming release.

Two Late To The Party

Two Late to the Party is a Calgary based folk duo who's music has been played across Canada. Their latest singles "R-V-M" and "Ghost in my bones" have been featured on Calgary's X929.9 Xposure, CKUA radio and their debut album "The Great Unraveling" has been ranked top 10 Folk, Roots, Blues albums by CJSR in Edmonton.

Formed by Adam Corkett and Alessandra Enns in the fall of 2017. Both Adam and Alessandra have a long singer/songwriter history, with influences ranging from indie-folk to bluegrass-country. As a pair, they have found a style that merges their past influences, creating an original sound that is simultaneously current and nostalgic. In 2018, Two Late to the Party released music videos for their songs “In Gold” and “Divine” and in 2019, they released their first single “Here With Me”.

In 2021 TLTTP has started working on their sophomore album which will be releasing later this year.

Rosebud Outdoor Concert Series

The Rosebud Festival Society has teamed up with Rosebud Theatre to put on a special concert experience. On Saturdays in July and August, with a few special Sunday performances, musicians from across Alberta will be travelling to Rosebud to perform live! These concerts will be presented to a physically distanced audience on Rosebud’s gorgeous outdoor stage next to the Opera House.

column8: Madi Allen is a singer/songwriter with songs about love and life. Her voice is a blend of pop and soul and her lyrics are relatable and honest. ***\n\nJesse Dollimont - A little bit country, a little bit bluegrass, and once in a while just a little bit rock and roll, Jesse is a combination of sincere and heartfelt lyrics, gorgeous vocals and soothing guitar.  She will charm you with her humor and musicality.

I Am The Mountain plays campfire soul music, and is currently based in Calgary, AB. Carefully woven throughout our songs is emotion and atmosphere. We feel the music, and want people to experience our songs in the way that they feel is fitting. Chat with a friend, dance uncontrollably, have an Old Fashioned (neat), or lay quietly, motionless, focusing on each and every syllable and note.

We bring in a variety of our past and present experiences, music tastes, and personalities. We’re a blend of classically trained instrumentalists, leaning on our jazz, soul, & folk inspirations like Typhoon, Dan Mangan, Hiatus Kaiyote & Christian Scott. We’re all a bunch of goofy eggheads who would love to talk music with you, share a memory, or jam out in a sweaty basement or street corner.  

Currently, we are working closely with Juno Award nominee, Nils Mikkelsen (AM Static), to create a six song EP that will showcase the bands groovy and soulful new sound. The Ep, We’re Here For Each Other, is set to be released in late 2017.

Ten albums into an already acclaimed career, Stephen Simmons sharpens his rootsy folk-rock with A World Without, a record that mixes the twang of country music — a genre that provided the soundtrack for his childhood in small-town Tennessee — with the sharp observations of a singer/songwriter and the stomp of rural, roadhouse rock & roll.\n \nA road warrior with an audience on both sides of the Atlantic, Simmons has spent most of his adulthood on stage, playing songs in ten different countries along the way. Recorded with members of his touring band, A World Without explores a life lived on the run, taking a look at the intersection between art, commerce, love, and travel. The songs are equal parts biography and fiction, with Simmons shining a light on those who travel and create for a living.

column8: This week's Alberta Spotlight lineup includes Astral Swans, Lucette, Mariya Stokes, Aladean Kheroufi, and Heather Blush & Captain Steve. \n\nAlberta Spotlight is a weekly online concert showcase that shines a light on Alberta-made music. The initiative is made possible through funding from the Alberta Government to support Alberta artists affected by COVID-19 and is brought to you by Alberta Music, National Music Centre, CKUA Radio Network, and Stagehand.

As 2020 draws to a close, we can reminisce about how Albertans have stepped up to make the best of our situation. We found joy in sharing our passions online with audiences that we’ve missed so dearly, and we collaborated in more creative ways than we ever thought possible. We watched as artists from across this province sang their hearts out and shared comfort with us through their music.

Earlier this year, The Government of Alberta, Alberta Music, the National Music Centre (NMC), CKUA, and Stagehand collaborated on the Alberta Spotlight series, a weekly digital concert initiative that showcased over 75 acts from across the province, providing free concerts for people watching from home and support to artists during the pandemic. We’re thrilled to offer one last special holiday concert to close out this year, featuring a variety of Alberta musicians including, George Canyon, Maddie Storvold, K-Riz, Lynn Olagundoye, and Joal Kamps.

Tips to the venue will be distributed to that artists.

column6: Fort Calgary Presents: Amelie Patterson and Sargeant & Comrade
column8:
Fort Calgary is thrilled to showcase a fierce double bill featuring Amelie Patterson and Sargeant & Comrade. This special event promises to be an unforgettable, intimate concert, including a meet and greet following the performance.


TICKET INCLUDES:

Assigned seating in our intimate Burnswest Theatre
A private post-show meet and greet with the artists, including complimentary beverages from Village Brewery and Rithet Coffee
Complimentary access to Fort Calgary's Interpretive Centre

Licensed event.

Tickets available online or at the door. 

Paid parking available on-site.

Please note that assigned seating is not guaranteed once the doors are closed. 

*****

About the Artists
AMELIE PATTERSON

Hailing from Banff, Alberta, and serving as the town’s first Poet Laureate, Amelie Patterson leads as a strong ambassador for women songwriters. The clear-voiced, honest and tenacious troubadour’s music traverses territories from blues to folk rock. Her debut album Roll Honey Roll was released in May 2016 at Canadian Music Week and went on to win YYC Alternative Recording of The Year in 2017. Patterson then took to the road touring across Canada hitting stages at Calgary Folk Music Festival, Banff Centre for Arts and Creativity, TED Talks, and venues across Alberta and BC.

www.ameliepattersonmusic.com


SARGEANT & COMRADE

One from Russia, one from Carribean, Sargeant & Comrade (Yolanda Sargeant & DJ Comrade) combine various cultures, styles and genres to create a unique sound that has been captivating audiences since this unlikely duo began playing live shows in 2009. Sargeant & Comrade combine elements of old school jazz, soul, reggae and hip hop to create brand new flavours of music that transcend genre. Dusty record samples get mixed with live instruments and Yolanda Sargeant’s stylish, soulful voice brings it all together. 

www.soundcloud.com/yolandasargeant

column6: SCOTT MORIN presents JAZZSEXY with Himself, JOHNNY SUMMERS, KODI HUTCHINSON, SHELDON ZANDBOER, JIM JOHNSTON & guest vocalist ANGELA WRIGLEY
column8:
Calgary, AB - This Sunday, September 5th will see Calgary’s most beloved live music venue continue their deep support for jazz and soulful music with the 2021 premiere of JAZZSEXY. Jazzsexy @ The Ironwood is a monthly celebration of soulful and groove-oriented jazz music, led by many of the leading musicians in the Calgary music community.
Nearly 10 years ago, Jazzsexy was borne out of the live-work loft of 3 Time Juno Award winning Producer, saxophone player and record label veteran Scott Morin. Back in 2012, Scott moved into a scrawling, 3000 ft. loft in the heart of Toronto’s entertainment district, near King and Bathurst. The Niagara Street loft was on the main floor of a massive warehouse building built in the 1880’s, one of the last of the illegal live-work artist warehouses in Toronto, and the former factory for the Heintzman piano company and a large coffin manufacturer in the early 1900s. In modern times, the warehouse became the home to dozens of visual artists, actors, musicians, poets and even a downstairs BDSM “dungeon”.! In addition, it was across the street from famed Director Atom Egoyan’s home, which led it to be included in some of his most famous films in various location scenes. The vibrancy of the arts community was alive on Niagara Street, and led to the inspiration resulting in a monthly jazz party at 91 Niagara Street, Scott’s home and creative space.
This monthly party soon became one of the most talked-about underground music events in Toronto, with celebrities, local news anchors, local and international musicians coming down to hang, sit in, and dig the music. The vibe of these parties was always celebratory – there was a 25 foot curved bar, a huge stage with grand piano and room for a large band, jazz awards and classic jazz photography from Paul Hoefler on the walls, and antique furniture all over the loft for folks to sit and enjoy the music from. Everyone from Grammy and Juno winners Roy Hargrove, Jeff ‘Tain’ Watts, Seamus Blake, Ron Sexsmith, JP Saxe, and dozens of others from the Toronto and NYC jazz communities came in to Jazzsexy to be part of the experience and play.
The name “Jazzsexy” came from Scott’s love of Jazz and the music of Prince. Prince recorded a legendary record in 1988 called “Lovesexy” which is where the brand for the concert series began. Prince’s spirit lives on through Jazzsexy concerts now, including arrangements of some of the geniuses’ classic songs.
Since moving back home from two decades living in Toronto, NYC and Vancouver, Scott Morin has been promoting and playing jazz and soulful music around Calgary as a secondary career, but is now focusing on a number of live music initiatives in Calgary, starting off with Jazzsexy @ The Ironwood!

column6: City of Calgary Anti-Racism Team, Public Safety, and Core Connections Resource Table - Bow Valley College
column8:
The City of Calgary acknowledges the existence of systemic racism. We will listen, learn, and build communities where racialized people and communities have equitable access to City services and programs.

Meeting public safety challenges requires the entire community to come together to better understand our strengths, our challenges, and our shared commitment. We intend to facilitate conversations within and between organizations by fostering a collaborative environment. As we collect input from the community, we will use it to shape further conversations and inform additional engagement.

Adjusting to life in a new country can be challenging. The Core Connections Program (C2) provides a fun space for youth who have recently arrived in Canada to integrate into the community and meet other youth. Core Connections is an ongoing program and focuses on the areas of community engagement, skill-building, and peer mentorship.

column6: Natural Twenty with I Am The Mountain
column8: Exploitatively groovy, Natural Twenty an eclectic vibe reminiscent of 90s hip hop laced with Latin groove under a dance punk & jazz inspired banner. Named after one of the most coveted dice rolls in Dungeons & Dragons, Natural Twenty aims to be a critical hit on stage.\nI Am The Mountain plays campfire soul music, and is currently based in Calgary, AB. Carefully woven throughout our songs is emotion and atmosphere. We feel the music, and want people to experience our songs in the way that they feel is fitting. Chat with a friend, dance uncontrollably, have an Old Fashioned (neat), or lay quietly, motionless, focusing on each and every syllable and note. We bring in a variety of our past and present experiences, music tastes, and personalities. We’re a blend of classically trained instrumentalists, leaning on our jazz, soul, & folk inspirations like Typhoon, Dan Mangan, Hiatus Kaiyote & Christian Scott. Alongside Juno Award nominee, Nils Mikkelsen (AM Static), we have created a six song EP that will showcase the bands groovy and soulful new sound. The EP, We’re Here For Each Other, is set to be released in early 2018.

column6: Tod Hughes with Guests: Spruce and the Meadowlark & Brady Enslen
column8: Tod Hughes is a Canadian storyteller, who writes real music that comes from the heart. A subtle message of hope is thread through the stories which are sometimes serious, and even a bit dark, while at other times slightly tongue in cheek. A live performance is guaranteed to be a fun event, which will leave you humming to yourself. \nRooted in the prairie's of Manitoba, Spruce and the Meadowlark deliver a fresh take on contemporary bluegrass. The combination of complex driving instrumentals and haunting melodic lyrics help to create a new perspective on the marriage of folk and bluegrass. \nSmall town prairie life is the heart and soul of Brady Enslen's music.  His songs and lyrics embody the nostalgic simplicity of growing up in rural Alberta; his steady-going guitar playing and accessible melodies create a backdrop for lyrics that are honest and meaningful. Brady's sincere presence engages listeners young and old, and makes one feel right at home.

Don’t underestimate this sweet and smoldering powerhouse. Born and raised in Okotoks, Alberta, Michela Sheedy pushes boundaries and brings well needed honesty to country music. Bringing pure Albertan steely edge to a genre where lines are often blurred, Michela is dedicated to writing songs that speak from the heart.

Danielle Dayton is a Calgary based artist who weaves vivid stories into her songs, accented by her deeply dark vocal timbre and soaring melodies. column8:
To Friends and Family of the Ironwood, 

When we lose a venue in Calgary, we lament it's loss and wish we could've done something to save a place that we cherish and value so dearly. We wish we could've done SOMEthing to save it. 

The time is now to come to the aid of our beloved Ironwood. They have but a few months before they are forced to close the doors permanently. We all understand these are unprecedented times in our Arts community. We cannot afford to lose this venue that is so vital and crucial to our City's music scene. 

More efforts will be done, rest assured, but for now we are throwing a fundraiser to show Pat, Amanda and the rest of the gang how much they mean to us and how much we love the Ironwood. 

All artists have donated their time to the efforts and we have received a flood of support from the community for our silent auction as well.

KEVIN KANE is a founding member of The Grapes of Wrath. As a solo artist, Kane has released the albums Neighborhood Watch (1996), Timmy Loved Judas Priest (2001), How to Build a Lighthouse (2007) & The Home Version (2011) which sees Kane revisiting songs from The Grapes Of Wrath and previous solo work live in the studio, with just his acoustic guitar for accompaniment.
kevinkanemusic.com / kevinkanemusic.bandcamp.com / FB @Kevin-Kane-9382189345 / IG/TW @kevinkanemusic

THE WILDERNESS is a Kingston, ON sextet with a propulsive, potent fusion of indie-rock and heartland punk having played 450+ shows and festivals across North America in the last four years. With band members from across Canada, US and UK, The Wilderness have independently released 10 singles, two EPs, a full-length, 40ish music videos, scored a Top 5 single and Top 20 album at national and BBC radio, given an award and earned comparisons to Bruce Springsteen, Mumford & Sons, The Lumineers.from fans and media. "This is our first time in Western Canada including a really special show in Calgary with Kevin Kane.We're humbled to have the privilege of performing these songs to new audiences for the first time. To Friends and Family of the Ironwood, 

When we lose a venue in Calgary, we lament it's loss and wish we could've done something to save a place that we cherish and value so dearly. We wish we could've done SOMEthing to save it. 

The time is now to come to the aid of our beloved Ironwood. They have but a few months before they are forced to close the doors permanently. We all understand these are unprecedented times in our Arts community. We cannot afford to lose this venue that is so vital and crucial to our City's music scene. 

More efforts will be done, rest assured, but for now we are throwing a fundraiser to show Pat, Amanda and the rest of the gang how much they mean to us and how much we love the Ironwood. 

All artists have donated their time to the efforts and we have received a flood of support from the community for our silent auction as well.

Calgary based singer-songwriter, Kearstin Pfeifer was born and raised in southern Saskatchewan and from a young age has had a passion for music. Outside of school, most of her days were spent teaching guitar lessons, participating in band and choir, and leading worship at her church. After high school, Kearstin continued to pursue music at Prairie College in the Music & Worship Arts program where she was mentored by Juno Award winning songwriter, Brian Doerksen. 
​
Kearstin's latest single Yahweh (Hear Your Name)" is nominated for Inspirational//Holiday Song of the Year at the 2022 YYC Awards
​
Kearstin's song "In the Quiet", co-written with Zac Parkinson was nominated for Folk Song of the Year at the 2020 GMA Covenant Awards and her debut EP "The Road Untold" was nominated for Best Saskatchewan Album of the year in 2019."

column8: Megan Dawson: "I am a singer/songwriter, playing my guitar and trying to make the world smile one song at a time. I have performed my original music at multiple venues throughout the city such as, Gravity Espresso and Wine Bar, Cowboys Casino Calgary, Ranchman’s Dancehall and many others. Following recording original songs at OCL Studios, I am very excited to release new music in the coming year for you all to hear."\r\n\r\nWe’re Jess & Robb, a girl, a guy, & acoustic guitars. “Dueting” in music and as a couple for the past two years has been wild! We celebrated the release of our self-titled debut EP in July at Café Koi. Since then, we’ve had the opportunity to perform around Calgary,  travel to Nashville for the CD Baby DIY musician conference, and play on the infamous Bluebird Café stage. Our music reflects the pop sensibilities of Taylor Swift, nonchalance of The Ramones, and the wit and heartbreak of Amy Winehouse. We can’t wait to connect and share our music and experiences with you!

column8:
To Friends and Family of the Ironwood, 

When we lose a venue in Calgary, we lament it's loss and wish we could've done something to save a place that we cherish and value so dearly. We wish we could've done SOMEthing to save it. 

The time is now to come to the aid of our beloved Ironwood. They have but a few months before they are forced to close the doors permanently. We all understand these are unprecedented times in our Arts community. We cannot afford to lose this venue that is so vital and crucial to our City's music scene. 

More efforts will be done, rest assured, but for now we are throwing a fundraiser to show Pat, Amanda and the rest of the gang how much they mean to us and how much we love the Ironwood. 

All artists have donated their time to the efforts and we have received a flood of support from the community for our silent auction as well. 

Need to know:
YES - you can buy a table and attend the shows
call 403-269-5581 for a table 
YES - you can donate/support online directly!

Honest, contemplative, uplifting and encouraging, personal yet relatable, surprising, moving.  Her voice has been called "strong, yet soothing and calming"  These are only some of the comments in response to Rhonda Louise's music.
Rhonda Louise lends everything within her to her songs.  "Songwriting is extremely vulnerable and revealing. It's somewhat of a musical diary," she says.  "Every song has a story behind it, as if to say 'Here is what I have felt, lived through, learned from, and what I have celebrated'.  When I am ready to share that memory with my fans it is an incredibly special moment."
Rhonda Louise shares her music within church services, coffee houses, bistros, house concerts, and in her concerts, tailoring her song choices to each unique group of guests.  "I love meeting everyone at my shows and enjoy hearing their stories, how they related to a song or a lyric."
 
As Rhonda Louise has grown as an artist, her songwriting continues to evolve and sometimes surprise her audience, and she looks forward to sharing those moments.  She also welcomes letters and emails, and appreciates knowing how her fans have related to her music.

column6: Book Release: Clem Martni’s new novel, The Comedian
column8:
In the Roman Republic, comedy is a serious business. Nobody knows this better than Titus Maccius Plautus, the principal comic playwright of his time. Licking his wounds after a series of artistic flops and financial disasters, Plautus returns from his refuge in the country to Rome, desperate to produce a new play. 

With limited financial backing provided by tough and striking bar owner Casina, Plautus recruits a company of actors from the amateurs and cast-offs he can afford. Led by a disreputable drunk who just happens to have a pedigree with one of the most respected traveling Greek acting guilds, the motley company unites an eccentric cast of characters on and off the stage. From Orestes, Plautus’ dour, thrifty director to the eager but untrained neophyte, Fronto, to the debt-plagued Plautus himself, each has a role to play, and each is not quite what they seem.

Can this company of misfits come together in time – and remain together long enough – to find success on the stage? With his creditors closing in, can Plautus stay one step ahead, or will he be finished, once and for all? Redolent with the sights and scents of the ancient world, this novel is a rowdy, boisterous ride through the realm of theater in its infancy.

column8: This Kootenay duo is a recent side-project of Clayton Parsons (The Good ‘Ol Goats) and Michael Hepher (Redgirl, As The Crow Flies). Both seasoned musicians in the area, Clay and Mike crossed paths at a mutual friends’ birthday party and ended up jamming the night away. That night of jamming turned into a regular thing that they’ve named The Doggone Brothers. The music is distinctly ‘grassy, with fishing, hunting and camping themes throughout their set of original and hillbilly cover tunes. Clay jumps back and forth between guitar and dobro while Mike picks the mandolin and guitar. They are sure to entertain as they keep it fun and loose while duelling back and forth with their respective axes.

column8:
❤️🎶
Szabo & Ladick - jazz, pop & crossovers: a lifetime of performing and the experience has curated a repertoire that spans genres. 

Kim Szabo and Bill Ladick, both originally from Canada, met in Osaka, Japan, while performing in different venues. Their chance meeting soon resulted in collaborative projects, and the realization that they had actually attended the same college. After Kim left Asia for Europe, they lost contact for many years, until by chance made contact again in Calgary. Once again, an opportunity came for them to reunite, and perform together.

“Home at Last” has a special meaning for both of them, from a reunited friendship, to new performance adventures here at home in Canada.

Szabo & Ladick - Home at Last - this Saturday!
Join Bill Ladick and myself at Vin Room West.
8561 8A Avenue SW    
tel 587-353-8812

Saturday November 27, 7-10pm.
Reservations recommended.

column6: Two Late to the Party with Natalie Inga
column8:
Join Calgary folk roots band Two Late To The Party and singer songwriter Natalie Inga for a night of original music and fun at Gravity Espresso and Wine Bar in Inglewood. 

Two Late To The Party has recently released their new single “All I Want Is Love” as part of their upcoming sophomore album “In The Sunrise”. Two Late To The Party performs their original music that ranges heartfelt to an uptempo indie-folk sound with lyrics that are meaningful with a deep folk vibe.

Natalie Inga is a Songwriter and Musician based in Calgary, AB. Earthy, spunky, and fierce, Natalie is a confluence of traits that make for bold, reflective, and graceful music, and an intimate, humorous live show. Raised on Canada's greatest folk music, Natalie brings a modern perspective to the tradition of writing for change. Because of her sweet voice, stacked harmonies, rich guitar parts, and bold messages, her most recognized influence is Joni Mitchell.

Little Ole Wine Drinker (the artist formerly known as Mark Cassano) is a guitarist/singer/songwriter based in Calgary. Think of him as the metaphorical musical love child of Nat King Cole and Dolly Parton.....  hmm... how about Willie Nelson and Norah Jones? Maybe Julie London and Lyle Lovett? Okay... that is not getting any less creepy, but you get the idea. His original songs are a blend of folk and jazz with a touch of blues and country. His set list consists of songs that he loves listening to and learning - and, here's the challenge, songs that he can do some semblance of justice to. They range from classic jazz standards to old time country to Americana. And he will make sure to play his wide variety of homemade mid-life crisis ballads and anthems. Recording will begin on his first solo album - he promises... soon...... he swears..... yep.....

2018 YYCMusic Awards Female Artist of the Year, Kate Stevens is an 18 year-old emerging artist who has been immersed in music her entire life. While scavenging through a garage sale, Kate found a used ukulele - a tool that shaped her music journey over the past 6 years. Her blended genre sound is an eclectic mix of emotive folk and soulful jazzy pop, with major influences from timeless voices such as Etta James, Ella Fitzgerald, and Joni Mitchell. Stevens likes to describe her sound as if Amy Winehouse and Carole King had a lovechild"\r\nHer unique soulful melodies are advanced yet approachable and truly heartfelt. Kate’s latest singles, "Right Choice" and  "it's real" follow her debut EP Handmade Rumours from June 2017. Kate is a powerful and engaging performer that captivates audiences of all ages. Kate is also the recipient of the 2018 Zachariah and the Prophets Memorial Award.

column6: Mason Jenkins with opener Cyd Hall.
column8: For Cyd Hall, words have always been a comfort. Whether it’s listening to someone’s story or spilling her own thoughts, the act is therapeutic. She uses music to convey that energy and pushes the love back into the universe. She’s just stepping into the incredible YYC art scene and will enjoy the adventure, wherever it may lead.\r\n\r\nMason's songs are velvet paintings. They are elegantly grafted and from a forgotten era and delightfully campy. His songwriting is built upon on a darkness that makes the listener ask out loud "...hey, is this guy ok?" He most definitely is, but it's best to come find out for yourself.

Elliott Steinberg finds inspiration for his singing from greats (old and new) Ella Fitzgerald and Mel Torme to Kurt Elling and Dianne Reeves. Elliott plays trumpet too, but finds great freedom in scat singing (improvisation) and wonderful expression in the beauty of a great lyric. He sings many jazz \r\nstandards, but more and more non-standards are filling his repertoire, including songs by Sting, Billy Joel, Gordon Lightfoot, and Stevie Wonder.\r\n

column6: Classical Rev YYC presents Revolutionary String Quartets
column8:
our instruments, eight hands, sixteen strings — it all adds up one of the most complex, versatile, and astonishing ensembles ever invented. Classical Revolution Calgary celebrates the string quartet, with an evening featuring music by Beethoven and other revolutionary composers!

Four young string players from the Calgary Philharmonic have recently formed a quartet, and this will be a early opportunity to see their new collaboration in action. Featuring Erin Burkholder and  Jeremy Gabbert, violins; Jeremy Bauman, viola; and Danny Poceta, cello.

They will perform Beethoven's String Quartet no. 10 ("Harp") and other works to be announced!

We will welcome open mic performers following the feature performance. Cover charge of $5 goes directly to support the members of the string quartet.

column8: Jacob Rose, with his acoustic guitar, has carved out a space for his own distinct sound by blending rock, folk and pop genres with political and philosophical subject matter. His song “Marco Polo” was a finalist in the 2016 YYC Music Awards and he recently played the Big Rock Barn Burner with Sam Roberts Band and Leeroy Stagger. \r\n\r\nJesse Shire is a singer-songwriter/multi-instrumentalist from Calgary, Alberta, who in the past three years has made himself a mainstay in the Western Canadian music scene. He’s performed at the Calgary Folk Music Festival, was a part of the inaugural Singer-Songwriter Residency at the Banff Centre, has recorded with Howard Bilerman (producer for Arcade Fire’s Funeral), shared songs with Jeff Hanna (of the Nitty Gritty Dirt Band), had music featured on both the CBC, has done a live show on BBC radio, and has performed north of the arctic circle. He’s a permanent member of Calgarian bands Rosalind and I Am The Mountain, and has performed with countless other groups from Alberta and BC. In early 2018 he toured the UK with Glasgow-based artist Carla J Easton, and in 2019 is planning on attended McGill University in Montreal, and will be releasing new material as a solo artist.

column8: ‘Johnny and the Stray Hearts is a local alternative-folk band from Calgary! Channeling intimate recounts of his past through vocal nuances and vivid lyrics, he also prophetically propels into the future with a rock and roll minded vision. OMJ oozes his ambience, his ever changing character identity and his perspective consciousness with every performance, on and off the stage, resurfacing as a fresh voice for Folk Music”

column6: Classical Revolution Calgary presents Jiajia Li on flutes
column8:
Timbre of Time (or, timbre de temps) An exploration of the spectral approach to music, originated fifty years ago in France by pioneer composers Gerard Grisey and Tristan Murail. Timbre was never a new word to the French, and the approach has been carried on by many other composers into modern day. Today we will be listening to these French composers’ work within the timbre of their time.


Also featuring music by Debussy and Jolivet, as well as Kaija Saariaho’s NoaNoa for flute and electronics — live electronics performed by composer Brian Garbet.

column8: Trust us when we tell you that this is a gig you do not want to miss.  Strongly suggest you make a reservation for this one!\r\n\r\nRaised in a small prairie town, Christina grew up in a musical family where the sounds of southern rock, country, gospel and blues could often be heard on playing on her Dad’s stereo.  Her first live performance was at 5 years old, and she learned to play guitar at age 12.  In her teens, she became enamoured with artists like Etta James, Mavis Staples, Nina Simone, The Band, JJ Cale, and Bob Dylan.  In 2014, Christina went back to writing, recording and performing after taking a hiatus to raise her three daughters, one of whom has a cognitive disability. She recently released an original project called “Uncaged".

column8: Join Bob Chartier and friends as they sing original songs and share original stories.

Come and listen to a voice described as “crisp, pure and powerful."  Danah-Lee’s last album, The Post Concussion Syndrome (December 1, 2017), has turned her very real-life experiences into songs. The album is a response to life unfolding – sometimes tragic and at other times euphoric.\r\n\r\nNOW - in 2019, the Ottawa Valley, Ontario-based singer songwriter has completed her latest EP, Sunshine & Bonbons (March 1, 2019). Danah worked with award winning producer Jordon Zadorozny (Courtney Love, Sam Roberts), and Phil Hulan (Belvue, Almost Kennedy), to record an album that is quite different than anything Danah has released before. Sunshine & Bonbons is one-part edgy, and one-part tug at your heart strings!

Holly is an indie-folk singer-songwriter who grew up in the moors of the Durham Dales in the North East of England. Her 2017 debut EP 'Ilex' launched her musical career with support from BBC 6 Music and a feature on Tom Robinson's BBC Introducing Mixtape. 2018 saw this success continue with festival slots at Hit The North and Evolution Emerging, as well as supporting the likes of CoCo and the Butterfields, Joseph J Jones, X Factor's Sam Lavery, and Hannah Trigwell.

This Frontier Needs Heroes is the moniker of singer-songwriter Brad
Lauretti, who in various forms and lineup changes, has spent the past 10
years playing shows all over the world. Logging thousands of miles in his
car, touring the greatest cities of North America and Europe, selling one
record at a time, making one fan at a time. This determination and DIY
ethos brought him on an epic journey around the world, playing listening
rooms, clubs, house concerts, and festival stages. One night with Brad will
run the gamut of all human emotions from humour, hedonism, activism and
heartbreaking sadness. From Folk-rock anthems, to indie folk, flares of
psychedelic, alt-country, to straight up storytelling you get it all in one
song. Influenced by songwriters like John Prine, Billy Bragg, Kris
Kristofferson, and Townes Van Zandt his timeless songs mix love, humor, and
protest seamlessly to get you through the tough times.

Tone Indbryn is a singer/songwriter who creates pieces woven from folk with mellow rock hints to support her lyrics laced with sardonic humour. She has performed in festivals, and local venues throughout BC, Ontario and Alberta, she is currently finishing off her 4th album   for 2019.

Gravity is pleased to present an intimate experience with reijo, truly one of Calgary’s and Alberta's hottest, talented, premiere rock n roll bands. Blending nostalgic 80’s edgy guitars, sweeping melodies, poetic lyrics and upbeat rock rhythms to create a new rock sound. You won’t want to miss this unique evening at Gravity.

Philip Adams has emerged from the Paris of the Prairies along with his indie/alternative tunes over the past three years. With a loop pedal, guitar, keyboard, and microphone, Philip creates a full-band sound as a solo artist, and Philip’s live performance and energy impresses fans of all ages.

column8: Kyle is a singer songwriter from Medicine Hat, AB. Influenced by writers like Jon Foreman and Gregory Alan Isakov; Kyle is marked with a passion for telling the truth and finding the beauty woven into every person's story. His laid back personality translates smoothly to the "easy listening" nature of his music, and his storytelling at live shows is usually equally as light and humorous as it is deep and thought-provoking. One of his latest singles was recently featured in Apple Music's "Best of the Week" playlist, and he is on tour this year showcasing his latest work, a 10 song album entitled, "Slow Down".

column8:
This promises to be a great evening of music!

Hole In The Hollow started as a solo project for Andy to be able to play to the softer side of his musical abilities. After going solo for a little while he decided to add members and create a full band sound. Adding Mackenzie’s vocals has brought depth and expanded harmonizing possibilities as well as it has deepened the stories told in the music. Chris’ bass allows for the music to be felt as well as heard, and Manuel’s drumming holds us all together and grabs the attention of listeners with unique fills. 

R&B singer-songwriter Zacarias plays with power trio and writes about intimate love, ethnic roots, and finding truth.

Singer-songwriter Ellen Adams works in folk and country traditions, with songs exploring longing, queerness, and the lies we tell ourselves and others in love. Drawing on the influences of Gillian Welch, Whiskeytown, old time, plus some Motown, she brings a little bit of twang and a whole lot of heart to the stage. She's performed in folk festivals and major cities on both sides of North America. Currently, she's artist-in-residence at University of Lethbridge's Gushul Studio, where she's recording her next album.

Ellen Adams will bust your heart open with songs about longing, queerness, and the lies we tell ourselves and others in love. She works in Americana traditions, drawing influence from Gillian Welch, Angel Olsen, old time, and a little bit of Motown.

Graham Nicholas is a Toronto based folk&roots songwriter. On Dial Tones and Pretty Notes, his latest full- length album, Graham Nicholas has created an emotionally resonant world inhabited by troubled and love-hungry characters. Never alienated for their insecurities, his characters are instead respected by the empathetic voice of an honest songwriter. The album finds Nicholas honing in on his concise form of storytelling and refining his irreverent sense of humour.

column8: Vocalist Erin Thrall is joined by Aaron Young (guitar), Mark DeJong (bass clarinet) and Donovan Seidle (violin) for a set of prairie-styled cover songs and other delights.

Part Bono, part John Lennon, and part Johnny Cash, James brings soul, a heart and meaning to his music. As the frontman of Calgary's rock act reijo, he brings raw energy and emotion to all he does. Experience James intimate and connect, finding uplifting power in his sweeping melodies and reflective, poetic lyrics.

The new saviours of rock n roll, reijo, are a Calgary, Alberta based rock band blending nostalgic 80's rock guitar tones, ambience and delays with thoughtful, socially-aware lyrics, creating a wholly rock sound with a modern update. 
often compared to an early U2, The Cure, Pink Floyd, reijo are an exciting act of energy and connectedness that are on the brink of taking rock in a new direction.
Catch them live here and now at Gravity.

Oleana, is a 4 piece folk/roots, band from Bragg Creek, AB. The group is known for its ability to weave back and forth between haunting melodies with sensitive arrangements, to toe-tapping, up-beat tunes, mixed with a good deal of on-stage humour and camaraderie. Their original tunes are well crafted and well received, but they still enjoy surprising their audience by sneaking in a few cover tunes!

Band in the Corner is back to liven up another evening with a lively batch of new covers and old favourites.  Doug, Marvin, Julianne and\r\nCharlotte collaborate to fill the cafe with an eclectic mix of acoustic melodies for all ages to enjoy.

Description
A performance described as Intense, edgy and dreamy, Notas de 4 with mexican singer Silvia Temis will bring you a very personal touch of Flamenco inspired music fused with traditional tunes from across Latin America.
This is a unique collaboration between Jorge Villena (Spain) on the guitar, Jonathan Lewis on the violin (Canada), Luis Tovar "El Pana" on percussion (Venezuela), and Silvia Temis vocals (Mexico) and dancer Maria Reigner (Calgary)
The set will include new songs by Notas De 4 and Latin/Spanish classics.

Carolina Slim is a singer songwriter from Mexico. Her music is pop - folk, she loves to write her songs in Spanish and English because is important for her that everybody understand that we are all brothers, no matter where we come from or what language we speak.

Singer/songwriter Wyatt C. Louis' dark, rustic tales of home blend folk with soulful blues.  Wyatt is gearing up to record and release parts of his first full-length this year.

Mason Jenkins and Kendra Lush provide an evening of music which would ease tensions between two romantic partners in a dispute over one person watching a few episodes ahead of a television series without the other partner, when it was agreed that the partners would watch the show together.

column6: Marshall Veroni with Emma Elena Grace
column8: Marshall Veroni is a deep cutting  contemporary folk singer songwriter with a recent full album and two tours under his belt. Veroni joins Emma Elena Grace, who's powerful lyricism and unique melodies are embodied by her own brand of alt-country folk, for a summer of touring and music creation. Their stop in Calgary at Gravity Espresso and Wine Bar will be positively moving.

The Josh Krushel Quartet presents the music of Wayne Shorter, described by the New York Times as “Probably Jazz’s greatest living small-group composer and a contender for the greatest living improviser”.  Combing elements of post-bop and modal jazz, these four musicians present a fresh energy, playing the compositions of one of the true greats.
In celebration of the long awaited film "Rocketman", spend an intimate evening with Rob Skeet as he takes you on a musical journey spanning five decades showcasing the music of Elton John.

”The Durbys are an Acoustic-Duo featuring Dan Jenkins and Milo Newton Fisher. The two focus on guitar weaving in a folk/blues/country style with original introspective lyrics and layered perspectives.”

Jeremy Gignoux is ever oscillating between calling himself a violinist or a fiddler. His Trio (with Nathan M. Godfrey on guitar and Aaron Scholpp on bass) plays entertaining instrumental music, drawing inspiration from jazz as well as North American and European folklore. His concerts have been described by listeners as "magical", "cinematic", "emotional", and "heart blowing".

column8: The Inglewood Night Markets are Calgary's premier night markets and a staple for getting out in the city in the summertime. 150 vendors, two live entertainment stages, food trucks and a licensed area! Come listen to and support the guitar students of the Legacy Gift of Music program. Since 2006, Legacy has been working hard to create all-inclusive music programming in Alberta that engages financially challenged families and vulnerable and at risk children and youth in potential life altering experiences.\r\n\r\nThrough the Gift of Music we have witnessed the powerful draw that music has for these young people and how significant this program has been in shaping the lives of this community's most vulnerable populations.

A new artist three decades in the making, singer / songwriter / guitarslinger Stephen King likes the suspension in life's changes, themes about hope, fear, fun, hiding and embracing sprinkle thoughout his music. The trio, Sarah's Last Day, will play original songs from Stephen's 6 CDs, including Nathan Krentz on upright bass and Steve Nykolyn on skins. The band bends dozens of influences when they play their mix of #americanada; indie-infused roots folk rock alt-country.
zpc* is dedicated to slathering your favourite music with a sweet layer of smooth, funky groove. The perfect summer evening date night music.

Nicole is an up and coming Calgary based artist who grew up in a musical family doing guest spots with her dad's band. Equally at home on keys or guitar Nicole has a deep love for music and for adapting classic songs to her own subtle style. She has experience playing corporate gigs and coffee houses and is always looking for a chance to share music with people that love it.

column8: Prairie-based singer-songwriter Blaeser combines elements of percussive, folk and fingerstyle guitar - acoustic arrangements that would be right at home on a drive from Regina to the Rocky Mountains. Played solo with a loop pedal or as part of a duo or trio, every song is a story that's ready to be told a thousand times.\r\n\r\nJake Hall, aka troubador Tort Muleyeus, has a powerful voice and a strong acoustic style all his own, ensuring you remember both long after the final notes have faded.

Completing a Music Degree from the University of Calgary, studying classical guitar and performing as a jazz vocalist, Georgie found her niche in music when she combined elements of these genres with her early love of country and blues music. She recorded her debut album “Since You Came Along,” in Nashville Tennessee.

Victoria Marquez and Daniel Hayes combine their talents to deliver an acoustic sound that is enchanting and exotic. Their music incorporates jazz, classic pop and Bossa Nova creating a unique, intimate and personal musical style.
Julie Olive is a singer-songwriter whose strong vocals and jazzy guitar has made waves across Alberta.
Magdalene Baker is an 18 year old singer/songwriter originally from Vancouver, BC but resides in Calgary, AB.Her sound can be described as the love child between Joni Mitchel and Taylor Swift.

column6: Two Late to the Party with Mono Pony
column8: For Two Late To The Party - Two Late to the Party are Adam Corkett and Alessandra Enns. This budding musical duo formed in the fall of 2017. Both Adam and Alessandra have a long singer/songwriter history, with influences ranging from indie-folk to bluegrass-country. \r\n\r\nMono Pony - Bertus Van Zyl originally started playing drums performing with a few bands including “Soil 7t7”.  Today he looks back and is fortunate enough to have played gigs in 5 different countries and he has played music with many amazing musicians on a regular basis in some of the most beautiful places on the planet.
Sonia brings her soulful folk sound and stories to us just days before she travels to record her debut solo EP in BC! Join her for a celebratory send-off!

Two accomplished singer/songwriters from different parts of the world have come together in Calgary to form this unique acoustic folk/roots duo called Dublin2Durban. Gerry Madigan, on vocals and banjo, hails from Dublin in Ireland, where he was weaned on the booming folk scene of the seventies. Katie Windt, on vocals and guitar, comes from Durban in South Africa, where she was involved in its vibrant music scene with her own band.

Total Gadjos is an Eastern European Folk inspired Post-Punk septet based in Calgary. The lineup is clarinet, sax, guitar, drums, violin, double bass, accordion, and trumpet. We play energetic, positive, and uplifting music that makes the heart dance and brings to mind Gogol Bordello, Nick Cave, Tom Waits, and Firewater.
Oleana is an original, folk / roots band from the hills west of Calgary. Great writing, arrangements, fun and heartfelt stories for an entertaining evening!

column6: Zacarias and the wonders with Whyatt C Louis and Sergeant & Comrade
column8: Get ready for a night of soulful music with bluesy folk singer-songwriter Whyatt C. Louis, the smooth and mellow sounds of Zacarias and the Wonders, and the stylish, soulful duo Sargeant and Comrade.

Sue Decker’s soulful voice, earthy slide guitar playing, and ‘outlaw country’ songwriting sensibility make for a powerful combination. In 2019, Sue is releasing her debut full length album Outskirts of Love, twelve original songs spanning solo country blues, evocative ballads, and full band soul arrangements.

Dean Lauderdale is a one-man-band who makes use out of his live looping to create a unique and spontaneous sound with his instruments. His original music is heavily influenced by works of The Beatles, Bob Dylan, Earth, Wind, & Fire, Daft Punk, Mumford & Sons and Ed Sheeran.
Join singer/songwriter and live looping wizard, Dean Lauderdale, for a terrific night of outrageous covers, original tunes and more!\r\n

Cayd is a passionate singer/songwirter, born and raised in Calgary.  He has been playing and performing music, locally and around Western Canada for over 10 years. When he performs as a solo artist,  he plays released and unreleased originals and covers ranging from the Beatles, Eagles and CCR to Needtobreathe, Paolo Nutini, Barnaked Ladies, Thomas Rhett and Ed Sheeran.

Join Premanition for an evening of sweet acoustic serenading, have a drink and some food to ease your Tuesday night. 

She will be performing songs from her new debut album, Head Games, as well as covers of some of her favourite songs!

Also joined by the lovely Mercy Lamola to open with performances on ukulele and piano, a variety of originals and cover music.

Nico is a Calgary-based singer/songwriter who plays a mix of original music and  contemporary and classic covers.  She is an engaging performer with a warm presence who has entertained audiences across the globe. Her latest EP,  "The Dream Factory"  was released in March 2019.
Calgary born and raised musician will keep you entertained with his smooth strong voice and unique finger picking style.

column8: Join Guitarist & Singer Brian Kennedy for an entertaining evening of Swinging Standards, Vintage Blues & Western Classics.
We welcome fellow performers and listeners to an open mic night, featuring classical musicians from your community! Hosted by pianist Joseph Fernando.

column6: Cornerstone Songwriters Cooperative hosted by Carolyn Harley and Co-hosted by
column8:
The Cornerstone Songwriters Cooperative!! 
The second Sunday of each month 1:00 - 3:00 
There will be time to visit and connect from 3-4 for anyone wanting to stay afterward. 
Carolyn Harley will be hosting this new event for songwriters and original music fans. This cozy venue will allow an intimate and casual way for songwriters to connect and create community. A different songwriter will co-host with Carolyn each month to perform and talk about their songwriting process. 
We will allow time for songwriters in attendance to perform their work and receive feed back if they wish. We are looking to create an opportunity for songwriters to get to know each other and share. 

Join Cornerstone Music Cafe in celebrating their for love original live music !!

This performance will take place near the YYC Letters located by door 16 in International Arrivals. Please park in P2 Long-Term parking.

Blending folk, roots, and country sensibilities, Danielle Knibbe's songs win, and then all too often, break your heart. This award-winning singer-songwriter puts on an impeccable live show with her trio, full of rich harmonies and carefully crafted lyrics.
Singer/ Songwriter Julia Roar presents a fresh Country sound that's warm, inviting, and from the heart.
dzpc* is dedicated to slathering your favourite music with a sweet layer of smooth, funky groove. The perfect summer evening date night music, all year long. 😎😍

From yodels to soulful ballads, Dean's velvety vocals, masterful guitar and eclectic songs span from the early 1900's to the present. He draws from many genres including country, folk, blues, classic rock, soul, Celtic and original songs.
Sarah-Ann is a singer-songwriter from Quebec. In the last year she played venues in the rockies and around BC. She's now ready to perform in Calgary. Her style is indie, pop & folk.

Mitch Belot entertains with his swampy story telling style and modern rock flare. He hooks audiences with his powerful, smoky voice, and gets them on their feet by incorporating fast tempos and heavy grooves. While he is first and foremost a humble student of the blues, Mitch adds a taste of rock to the naturally ear pleasing sound that permeates his repertoire.
Head in for toe tapping jazz as Genevieve Phillips is joined by Peter Streitman on Guitar, Reese Perry on electric bass and John McNeil on drums.

Amy Lee Owens is a published r&b soul singer and songwriter. With a sense of pure feeling and passion inspired by classic r&b and soul records of the early 70s, Amy finds herself conjuring up and delivering songs both carfree and retrospective, tender and bold, sensitive and self-assured. This smooth soul singer will leave you wanting more, luckily her original songs are available on all music platforms. Amy sings a unique mix of self written originals and classic r&b covers.

A duo that combine old and modern music with new heart, ukulele, guitar, and the occasional kazoo!

Hailing from Calgary, the band plays a musical cocktail of original music from lead guitarist/singer Stephen King’s 6 CDs, along with varied covers from Wilco, Josh Rouse, Neil Young, Rihanna, Hendrix, Killers, Black Keys, Rancid, Bob Dyan, SRV, Ryan Adams, Nirvana, Beck amongst many others … all of which Sarah’s Last Day molds to their own inimitable style.\r\n

Patchwork Yak is a Calgary-based roots band comprised of Murray Fitch, Suzi Martin and Erik Smistad playing music ranging from gentle and sweet to rowdy with a solid groove.  Expect original songs and a few select covers that will make you move, think, laugh and sometimes cry.

Mike Jones on piano, John McNeil on drums, Reese Perry on bass, Michael Callander on trombone and Steve Williams on tenor saxophone. column8: Inspired by rockabilly music from the 50s’ and 60s’ and his love for honest songwriting, Clint is developing his own brand of country. His mission is to create heartfelt music that brings out emotion in his listeners.
Damase Elis is a Calgary born singer-songwriter blending folk tales with a contemporary edge & haunting voice.

Two Late To The Party is a Calgary based folk duo featuring the songwriting styles of Adam Corkett and Alessandra Enns. They have merged their styles together to create sound that is fresh and soulful. They will be joined by the fantastic Robert Adam, Robert combines his roots in the soulful simplicity of classic country with lyrics that offer more than surface meaning.
Our pre-Halloween happening features pianist Eric Nyland, performing masterpieces by Bach and Beethoven, followed by an open mic featuring regulars and guests.

Recently back from her European tour, International Recording Artist, Calgary's own, Claudia Santiago performs at Gravity Espresso and Wine bar Wed, Oct 23 7-9pm! Come enjoy an intimate evening of upbeat and smooth pop/R&B/soul/jazz/latin jazz covers and originals! Joining Claudia on guitar is Justin Hazel. Bring your friends or enjoy a mid-week date night out with great music, delicious food and 50% off wine bottles!

Rob Skeet is a live entertainer with over 30 years of experience in the entertainment industry, playing guitar and keyboards and working from a centre of electronic gizmos and whatzits, Rob uses his boundless energy to create an evening of fun and merriment. Now with the addition of a smokin’ celtic fiddler,  Rob offers up a Duo alternative as “Rob Skeet and Clay Pigeon”

Join accoustic folk/roots duo Dublin2Durban  for a fun night of song and stories.

Johnny Summers, one of Canada's best and busiest tumpet players, teams up with jazz guitarist Pat Moore, and one of Alberta's most in demand standup bass players, Kodi Hutchinson, for an evening of swing and mellow jazz!

Retrofile are a Canadian music duo formed in 2016 by twin brothers Luke and Noah Martino. After disbanding from an indie rock project, the two began experimenting with drum machines and synthesizers. Their debut Single "Two Words" was self released in the summer of 2017 to positive critical reviews. The track has gone on to accumulate half a million streams on AppleMusic, Spotify, and YouTube.

The Buggs are a Calgary based five piece bluegrass and roots music band playing covers and originals. Years of traversing Alberta's folk, bluegrass and roots festivals and folk clubs have forged a sound laced with plenty of experience, inventive instrumentation and glorious vocal harmonies.

Lanice Chep is a non-binary Okotoks singer-songwriter who has an affinity for all things honest and heartfelt while creating a relaxing coffee-shop-esque atmosphere for the audience. Beautifully  matched with modern folk guitar, their lyrics are soft and yielding and are deeply rooted in personal experiences.


Southern Alberta songstress Hanna Taylor  has a refreshingly powerful yet soft voice that is capable of shifting melodies into a world of their own. Having grown up between Canada and New Zealand, her lyrics reflect the small nuances of cultural disparities and leave the listener with either a sense of curiosity or a thought provoking story.

Sean Isaac – Author of Mixed Climbs in the Canadian Rockies and Editor of the Canadian Alpine Journal

Sean is a prolific mixed, rock, ice, and alpine climber, having climbed and made first ascents in Canada, and interesting big mountain venues like Peru, and Kyrgyzstan amongst many others.

Based in Edmonton, Canada, “Just Worry!” is the latest EP release in 2018 and was played on local radio (NOW radio 102.3) and well received by online fans of the band. New EP "I Saw" to be released by the end 2019!!\r\n\r\nInfluenced by their diverse musical tastes, Meadow Drive puts a new spin on some of your favourite styles - everything from alternative to jazz, to 80's pop.

David Dallas has been steadily building a name for himself as one of the up and coming guitarists of Alberta. A native Calgarian, David has spent most of his music career playing in the city he grew up in, as well as in the provinces’ capital. He has also performed in a variety of clubs, bars, and festivals around Alberta and in British Columbia. Some of the styles that he has dedicated his life to learning and performing include Jazz, Blues, Rock, Country, Americana, and Folk.  Join the David Dallas Group as they perform modern jazz arangments of contemporary classic songs.

A highly talented guitarist and a writer of songs that can touch the heart or tickle the funny bone – Neil Speers is an experienced performer based in Calgary. This summer he released his latest CD Snapshot Blues.

Skookkum is comprised of singers/songwriters Janine Bracewell & Jeff Kushner. It is the smaller, more acoustic sibling of Calgary band MoFaux. Their songs are about love and longing, joy & sadness and beautiful covers from Ryan Adams, Jeff Buckley and Emmylou Harris. Melodic songs and seamless harmonies.. a little shoegazing and a little folk...

Singers from a broad spectrum of ages, genres, and skill levels are preparing to showcase their learning after 5 months of weekly private vocal lessons.
